observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor instruct the City General Services Officer, OIC-
City Accountant, and the Inventory Committee to continue the execution of the one-
time cleansing of PPE balances by adhering to the guidelines and procedures for the
six activities prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006, enumerated below:

i. Preliminary activities prior to the conduct of inventory taking;
ii. Inventory taking;
iii. Reconciliation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting
records;
iv. Disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs;
v. Procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available
record of accountability; and
vi. Accounting entries and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

1.12. We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
1.12.1. Coordinate with the Municipal Engineer in identifying the projects that have been completed but remained recorded under the CIP accounts;
1.12.2. Record the transfer of the costs of the completed projects from the CIP accounts to the respective PPE accounts once these are identified;
1.12.3. Record the transfer of the PPE accounts from the Trust Fund to the General Fund and subsequently record the receipt thereof;
1.12.4. Record the corresponding depreciation expenses for the current and prior years;
1.13. We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer establish a regular monitoring process of the Municipality’s CIP accounts to ensure the timely transfer of completed projects to the appropriate PPE accounts.

We recommended that the City Mayor, at the earliest practicable period, initiate the One-Time Cleansing of PPE balances of the City by following the guidelines and procedures on the six activities enumerated below, to eliminate the noted discrepancy amounting to P30,427,525.77 as of December 31, 2023:
1. Preliminary activities prior to the conduct of inventory taking;
2. Inventory taking;
3. Reconciliation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting records;
4. Disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs;
5. Procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability; and
6. Accounting entries and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that:
1. The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer reconcile the difference between the RPT and SET Receivables account balances totaling ₱18,359,226.24 and henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation, together with the Municipal Assessor, of the total collectibles from the Basic and Special Education Tax with the balances of the RPT Receivables and SET Receivables accounts to avoid accumulation of unreconciled differences;
2. The Municipal Assessor prepare and submit to the Municipal Treasurer an assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties on or before the thirty-first (31st) day of December each year;
